tspan.tspan: Imperial Election
If you have control over any Electors, use their votes to vote for a player to become Emperor. Vote
for any player of your choosing. If voted for, you may not refuse becoming Emperor. Unaligned
Electors vote as a block for the orthodox player with the most votes after all Players have voted.
Use Initiate to break ties. If a majority cannot be secured, elect Emperor by a plurality.
On election, take 2 Imperial Power and additional Imperial Power equal to the round number,
starting at 1 extra Imperial Power. Place one of your provinces on the left.
Death and Reelection of the Emperor
Reelect the Emperor if they have been Emperor for two rounds, if they died, or if they became a
Foreign Power since becoming Emperor. If the Emperor has been Emperor for only one round, roll a
d6. On a 3 or less, the Emperor dies.
Perks of being the Emperor
Take the first turn whenever Initiative is used.
If you use a French Interference token during your vote for the Council of Trent, delay the Council.
Decide who wins during a tie in the Peace of Westphalia victory type.
Ignore Influence costs for taking non-adjacent provinces from a Foreign Power.
Take one extra opprotunity to join a League once everyone has chosen.
If you take part in a victorious League War, replace any Heretical Electors with other Orthodox
Principalities of your choice.
Block Religious Victories of the heretical faith.
Tradeoffs
Gain 1 Influence if Foreign Powers other than the Emperor owned no provinces in the Empire this
round. Gain 2 Influence if the Emperor or their allies conquered at least one province from a Foreign
Power this round. Lose 3 Influence if Foreign Powers that you did not go to war with own provinces
in the Empire. Any Influence gained or lost in this way may be placed in or taken from your stored or
placed Influenced.
